comment.editorialComment: By now, any impact from the increase activity around the new plate in September is likely to have lost its momentum and now we expect values in this sector to start to come under a little bit of pressure as we go through the month. This is likely to be driven by both the drop off in retail demand and subsequently, the lack of desire by trade buyers to buy speculatively as we approach the end of the year. This usually means that values move back more than they have in previous months and we expect to see an overall movement of around -2.0% by the end of November.

In recent years values in this sector have been fairly stable with no real surprises in terms of drops. However, December is the month where there will still be some stock around but the reality is that there will be less appetite from the trade to buy it unless it is priced realistically. This is the time of the year when vendors are trying to clear inventory before the start of the new year and buyers are aware of that and will bid accordingly. The nett effect of this is that values will inevitably come under some pressure and we would expect to see a drop of -2.5% during the course of the month.

We would normally expect to see an increase in demand from both trade and retail buyers alike as we go into January. Many dealers will be pushing for extra business by using strong marketing programmes to help generate extra footfall and to help gain some momentum after the Christmas break. This normally has a positive effect on the market and there is no reason to believe that this sector shouldnt benefit from this. Used vehicles in this sector tend to represent good value for money and consumers will often find it an easily justifiable decision on the back of low interest rates and strong desirability. Our view is that we may see a small rise in values as we go through January.
